76561197978272147,Recommended,255260,11535647,"Posted: 3 August, 2014",all,Max Pavo,"This is my opinion on the Pro Cycle Manager 2014. This is my first purchase into this franchise series.Disclaimer: I am not involved in professional or amateur cycling and have no knowledge about managing a cycling team. I am just a gamer.Rather than a deep dive into every aspect of this game I prefer to distill this down to a few points.I will not cover the multiplayer mode, or Career Mode, I have not participated in multiplayer as of yet, and career mode seems to me overly done.1. What enticed me to purchase this?For me, I thought it would be fun to manage, train, and race my cycling team around the many different circuits.  To outfit the team colors / sponsorship, bike frames, wheels, etc would be nice attributes for a cycling game.After Purchase:After downloading nearly 11gigs and doing the install, the game loaded without error and runs fine on my machine using the maximum settings. So, I am not too sure why others had/have crashes, maybe early versions of the game was problematic, I am using 1.3.1, Overall the game is stable and runs fine.Graphics:I have no real complaints, the ""effects"" and rendering are pleasant enough for realism, you have control over the color saturations, and in game special effects.  One thing I did notice is all the duplicate bystanders along the routes, basically you have about 10 different bystander and they repeat which is very obvious, as well as photos of riders.  Not that this matters since each rider is measured by his stats not his photo.  The other minor issue is with vehicles going through riders, mostly at corners.Camera Angle:The in game camera allows for a few fixed views, mimicking those angles you would see on TV during a real race. You can step through these using shortcuts or via the side menu.  I do wish they offered a free view, so I could put the camera behind my rider facing the challengers or on the handle bars etc..Game Play:Depending on how you approach playing this game will dictate your experience. What I mean by that statement is this game offers a ""Career"" mode which involves you in every aspect of managing a team; even to the point of scheduling, scouting for new talent, purchasing, salary, picking your team, calendars, answering mail, assigning members to training camps, setting objectives, trying to meet your sponsor objectives for scheduled races. - So, career mode is the long term play mode that involves all the tedious duties necessary to run/manage a racing team. With career mode you will not be immediately racing until you satisfy several pre-season task and for a lot of people this may be too much to do or frustrating.The game does offers single non-career races that you can participate in. Unlike the career mode nothing in the single race is too overwhelming, You select, go through a few screens and your racing.  So for me this is where I mostly find myself unfortunately due to my aversion of the career mode requirements.  In non-career mode you select your team & riders, set objectives/strategy and show up for the race, then send commands/orders to riders via the riders interface.What’s wrong for me?In Non-career; I feel detached from the game and my team. During races, I simply move some sliders around an position riders as the race progresses.I want to like this game so much, but it does not contain enough substance to keep me drawn in.  I wish there was a simple TEAM mode where you choose team members, have the ability to take your team to training areas within a country/local and build up experience, fitness and other attributes and develop sponsorship as you build up and win races.Final Thoughts:CYANIDE founded a great franchise in ""cycling”, there is room for improvement in several areas and I hope the game evolves to include more interaction and involvement with actual building of characters dialog with team members and with the inclusion of 3D training routes you can take your team to increase their attributes in real time.  Overall the game does offer cycling fans enough to keep them coming back for races and if you so desire,  a career mode for those who like diving deep into the management aspect.  For me, I would prefer a more streamlined “Team Mode”option.Is it worth $$, if you like or are a fan of cycling – yes,If you want to deep dive or have a desire to manage a cycling team – Yes, this is the only game in town.If you want real-time 3D “character” race simulation and control – probably is not worth spending your $ on."
76561198007825491,Recommended,255260,11179021,"Posted: 11 July, 2014",all,Tableworm,"Update:After tuning down my graphic settings a bit, the game rarely crashes, and has actually become enjoyable. The season planning tools is a highlight in this years release, and is definatly something that makes this version a lot more enjoyable to play in comparison to older releases.Like most manager games, you'll need basic knowledge about the sport to really immerse yourself in the gaming experience, so I'd say that this game is still mostly for cycling enthusiasts.The AI is actually pretty realistic, like in real life, the Tour de France in my career had a pretty random outcome, since most of the favorites lost a lot of time on the cobblestone stage in Britain, was lucky to have my team captain in the front group, which ended up landing me a spot in the top 3.The game as a whole looks better than last years installment.The UI is a lot more intuitive than in previous games of the series.The AI actually seems pretty well balanced, and it seems like computer controlled riders can also have a bad day, which can come in handy, especially in the stage races."
